## Part 1: Laws of Thermodynamics

Thermodynamics literally means "the movement of heat." There are four laws, but two are critically important for Environmental Sciences.

### Zeroth Law (the foundation)
If object A is in thermal equilibrium with object C, and object B is also in equilibrium with C, then A and B are in equilibrium with each other. This is just how temperature works — it lets us define and measure temperature consistently.

### First Law — "Energy cannot be created or destroyed"
Energy only changes form. When you burn coal (chemical energy), it becomes heat energy and light. That heat warms water, which becomes steam, which spins a turbine (kinetic energy), which generates electricity. At every step, the total energy in the universe stays the same — it just transforms.

**Environmental relevance:** When we burn fossil fuels, we are not "making" energy — we are releasing energy stored by ancient plants millions of years ago. We cannot get more energy out than we put in.

### Second Law — "Every energy conversion produces some waste heat; disorder always increases"
This is arguably the most important law in environmental science. It introduces the concept of **entropy** — a measure of disorder or randomness. Every time energy is converted from one form to another, some of it becomes low-grade, unusable heat.

Two key consequences for the environment:

1. No energy conversion is 100% efficient. A car engine converts only about 25–30% of fuel energy into motion; the rest is wasted as heat.
2. Energy flows in one direction: from **concentrated (high quality) → dispersed (low quality)**. You cannot spontaneously reverse this without doing work.

**Environmental relevance:** Ecosystems work because the Sun constantly pumps high-quality energy into Earth. Without this input, entropy would cause all life to wind down. This is also why nuclear and fossil fuels are so valuable — they are stores of concentrated, high-quality energy.

