## Part 4: Material Balance (Mass Balance)

This is one of the most practical tools in environmental engineering. The fundamental principle: **What goes in must equal what comes out plus what accumulates inside.**

Written as an equation:

> **Accumulation = Inputs − Outputs ± Transformation**

If inputs = outputs and no transformation occurs, the system is at **steady state** — the concentration stays constant over time.

### Where you will use this:

In **air pollution control:** A factory emits a pollutant; the wind carries it away; some deposits on the ground. A mass balance tells you how much is building up in the atmosphere.

In **water quality management:** A river receives sewage effluent (input), dilutes it with river flow (mixing), and the BOD gets degraded by bacteria (transformation). A mass balance tells you what the downstream water quality will be.

In **waste management:** A landfill receives solid waste (input); some degrades to gas (transformation); the rest accumulates. A mass balance tracks the total mass over time.

The concept of a **control volume** is key — you draw an imaginary boundary around the system you are studying, and then you account for everything crossing that boundary.

